I agree we should defend ALL beliefs in this nations..the majorities and the minorities. We should protect each and every one ALL equal and ALL the same. But we should not make special concessions for the minority just because they are the minority. For example: 10 people enter a room...eight Christians and two Muslims. They all agree that the want to pray and worship their god...so they begin. Obviously the eight Christians are 'dominating' the rooms airwaves with their prayers cause the are the majority. Now Joe and Sally Muslim are offended cause they don’t want to hear the Christians pray. So they write their congressman, senator and president to tell them. The government, applying socialism to the event, pass a law forbidding anyone to pray in that room ever solely because it was not fair to everyone...BS! And that is basically what we have today in the public schools. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Would you want to hear a Satanic prayer?  Or a pagan one?  I think Christians are fine with prayer in school as long as it is their prayers.  <br>
<br>
Try to imagine how it must be to be a minority.  Imagine you move to Utah and are in a predominatly Mormon area.  While Mormons are Christians, their extra book changes and modifies a lot of the rules.  Would you want your daughter going to school and being told by her friends that she is going to Hell unless she converts to Mormonism?  Would you want her to listen to Mormon prayers every day?  Do you think she would feel comfortable saying her Babtist prayer in front of her schoolmates?<br>
<br>
School is an environment to grow and learn.  It is fine to have a religion, but when it appears to be sponsored by the school, it creates problems for the minority.  Just put yourself in the minority's place and think how you would feel if the roles were reversed.<br>
<br>
Scott (Quath) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ubrutas222.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brutas222</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 277<br> <font color=#E9D756>(5/24/02 10:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Simple, Clear and Poweful</span><hr size=1> <br>
Quote:<br>
I can care @#%$ less that there are more of your kind than mine.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    ROFLMAO   I agree but of course disagree as well.  Its hard to live with so many different people, cultures, creeds, ethnicity’s etc….  Rheaton was correct when he said we would stop paying taxes if we knew what they went for.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
Would you want to hear a Satanic prayer? Or a pagan one? I think Christians are fine with prayer in school as long as it is their prayers.<br>
<br>
Generalities such as love, truth, discipline, empathy etc….. are acceptable in my opinion.  The above ’prayer’ brings attention to some very neglected issues.  The prayer has a positive intention however it does get a little too descriptive for the Non-Christian.  It does not cause a big social problem IMO.  If there were a much larger Non-Christian minority it might, but that is not the case.  <br>
<br>
Many times, moral issues aren’t clear because they are not by themselves doctrine.  They are doctrine when someone makes an attempt to specifically intertwine their personal feelings with some sort of logical philosophy.  I think if there were a Buddhist monk giving the prayer, he would have mentioned love and truth just as the Christian did.  In fact, it would be a breath of fresh air to see some other religion profess truth and love on an issue.  I think it would make Christians realize how far away they’ve gotten from such.  <br>
<br>
Unless your religion is on the warpath, there is little reason to mind anyone of any religion professing positive thoughts and feelings. What if a religion says, “sorry god, for we have not sacrificed a virgin to day, for all of them have been fvcked already”.   Obviously our laws do not completely protect the rights of everyone.  <br>
<br>
The most interesting thing I find in this arguement is the pride that is under attack.  People who take a nationalistic type pride in their religion, for example; &quot;I'm a Baptist, a follower of God's word and keeper of faith, kneel down brother and sumbitbefore you are cast into the depths of hell&quot;  NOW, for once, these c0cksuckers realize how damn stupid they are for saying such bvllshit.  These piece's dung might soon realize that they pray to their institution rather than God himself.  From a Christian perspective, I see these ignorant, institutionally brainwashed freaks as getting dose of their own medicine.  (I'm generalizing as there are these type of people everywhere)     <br>
